description.text:
This is a small handle designed to hold a thumbtack, used to clean Up! cellboard.
The Up! 3D printers from PP3DP use a perforated cellboard for their build plate. The system seems to work pretty well, the molten filament flows into the perforations, securing the raft and your printed object. The problem is poking the left over plastic out of these tiny holes. A thumb tack is a good size, but is too small to hold for any length of time. This makes that task easier. Made in Autodesk 123d Design.
The thumbtacks that I use have a 7mm top end.  It took a bit of pressure to get it pressed into the handle.

comments.text: I own the Up mini and can confirm that you do not need to clean out the perf board- the raft from the next print will adhere to the plastic stuck in the perf and it will come out when you remove the print.  You do want to use the scraper to ensure that the board is completely clean.  I have also noticed warping on bigger prints but haven't been able to eliminate it.  My printer also doesn't handle pla well,  but I am not using official up brand pla so that could be it (doubtful,  I think it is an inherent flaw in the way it extrudes)
comments.author: JersyBeast

comments.text: There really is no need to remove the old plastic filament that melts into the perfboard.

Here is another iteration of an ellipsograph, this one has a larger range of major/minor axes ratios, compared to the first. ( ~ 1.41 - 1.77 )  
To facilitate the larger ratios, smaller screws were needed (6-32 instead of 10-32). This in turn wouldn't allow the nuts to be hand-tightened, so I added a piece and changed the arm to allow for step-wise changes of the ratios. Different sides of the arm have different cutouts to allow for the entire range to (feasibly) be used. The pen holder still requires 10-32 screws and 2 nuts.

You will need a 6-32 tap, a 10-32 tap, two 6-32 x 1" screws (1" or so), one 6-32 x 0.5" screw, two 10-32 nuts, and 2 10-32 screws, if you want to assemble this the way I did.  The washer (bushing) is difficult to get to snap over the saw-toothed region, but once it's in there, it  moves much easier. The 0.5" screw is used to collapse the arms on the bushing to get it to not move while drawing.

description.text: This Is a printable 3d printer I designed to display the build volume of the 12 cubed printer. I still need to work on the bed and some fine tuning.  I will be running the print soon. Build area is about 6". I will later be developing other sizes.

description.text:
Our dishwasher clip not only broke, but vanished as well.  I remember trying to find one on the web before, but decided it might be quicker to just print a replacement, so here it is.  Besides I don't have to wait for it to ship, and this is pennies compared to whatever I'd have to pay.  
Picture shows the new printed one and one of the original parts.  
Support
If you find my stuff useful, please check out my youtube Lego R2-D2 http://youtube.com/myL3G0 (ad pennies you know).
Printing & Installing

This is a little thicker on the back and might be a bit stiff to put in.  I printed on Makerbot "standard" at 20% infill (I didn't want it to fall apart).  I used a support because the clippy part is a little bit recessed.  Use care when installing, mine was stiff.  You could consider trimming the back to make it bendier, but it seems to work.  Or maybe make the points not spread quite so far.  Also the clippy parts seem a little too skinny (thickness).  The real one was less recessed.  
How I made it

I scanned a clip @ 200dpi, then dropped that into sketchup.  I used a calculator to figure out how big the resulting flat thing was and how much to shrink it to get it to fit.  (The .skp sketchup file has the scan still in it, just unhide it to show it).  
Then I kinda traced the outline, however mine was a little bent toward the middle, so I made the clip ends a hair wider.  I then used the pull tool to stretch it about the right height (measured with a tape measure), and again for the clips to make them a little skinnier.  
As I said, it's a tad tight, but seems to work well enough first try.  I suppose if it breaks in a month I might try to figure out how to make it a little less springy, but again, they're easy to print.

In an attempt to improve the overall performance of the 3drag, and with a handful of 608ZZ bearings at hand, I wanted to create an x/y axis bearing adapter. title: Filleted parametric wade's projector ceiling mount

description.text: This is a remodeled version of Wade's projector ceiling mount, but with smaller holes (M5 with 0.3mm clearance) and filleted arms. This includes fillet.scad from https://github.com/clothbot/ClothBotCreations/blob/master/utilities/fillet.scad, which generates very nice filleted joints. The projector plate is redesigned for the BenQ W1070+ (a.k.a. HT1075), and is parametric so you can generate one for any projector if you figure out the XY-coordinates of the screw holes in mm. Update: The filleted swivel piece snapped pretty easily when the arms are squeezed inwards with one hand. I'm printing another copy of both versions of the swivel piece to determine if the fillet was a good idea or not. Update #2: Both new pieces snapped with about the same amount of force. Perhaps the base of the swivel piece needs to be expanded. Update #3: Expanded the interface between swivel.stl and ceiling-plate.stl. This should make both stronger. Update #4: The projector plate was bending down along the center, so I added some stiffeners to increase its strength. Warning: Some projectors (such as the Benq W1070+) have air intake holes at the bottom where the plate attaches. If you have one such projector, be sure to put some spacers or standoffs between the plate and the projector, e.g. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1391946, to give it room to breathe.

Bill of materials:
  • projector-plate.stl (possibly customized for your projector)
  • swivel.stl
  • ceiling-plate.stl
  • ProjectorUniversal2.stl from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:4146
  • 2 x M5x50 (or longer) screw
  • 1 x M5x20 screw
  • 3 x M5 nylock nuts
  • 3 x M4 screws (however long you need for your projector -- the plate is 5mm thick)
  • 3 x M4 washers
  • 11 x M5 washers
  • 4-12 x M5 screws and washers (for ceiling plate)
    • Steps to assemble:

  • Thread the swivel to the ceiling plate in this order:

    • M5 nylock nut
    • M5 washer
    • ceiling plate
    • M5 washer
    • swivel
    • M5 washer
    • M5 screw

  • Thread the swivel to the universal joint (ProjectorUniversal2.stl) in this order:

    • M5x50 screw
    • M5 washer
    • first arm of the swivel
    • M5 washer
    • universal joint
    • M5 washer
    • second arm of the swivel
    • M5 washer
    • M5 nylock nut

  • Join the projector plate to the universal joint in the same manner as step 2.

  • Place assembled mount against the projector and secure it with screws.

  • Place the entire assembled mount + projector against ceiling or mounting piece and secure it with M5 screws.

title: Corn Butterizer for Trader Joe's Butter w/ Baseplate

description.text:
I love 3dGringo's Corn Butterizer, but I had to trim down the sides of my Trader Joe's butter sticks to make them fit. (I used the trimmings on a waffle, FYI.) So I enlarged the butterizer and added a baseplate.  Note that Trader Joe's butter sticks are not square... one of the sides is approximately 2 mm longer than the other, so the printable objects aren't square either. The objects fit snuggly, but if you have trouble, just add butter.  
There are two versions of the cornhole object (ha ha ha). One version has 3dGringo's curved end for corn and the other has a flat end for pushing up and slicing off the butter with a knife.  
I used red t-glase because it's reportedly food-safe, but all filaments become sterile at 100°C. I use rubbing alcohol to keep it clean.

t-glase I have a .40mm nozzle, but I fudged the nozzle diameter with S3D and reported a .55mm nozzle w/ .40mm layers. I learned this trick from 3DUniverse and it seems to help a lot of t-glase extruder gear slipping. 228°C

title: Space Shuttle on launch pad - fixed

description.text: For ROTOSCAN's Space Shuttle on launch pad model. For the aft section of the orbiter I reversed one face on the wing section and several faces on the tail. This should slice better for people having trouble printing this section. For the mid section of the orbiter I added a peg hole for attaching to the external tank. Hope it's in the right place. For the fore and aft sections of the external tank the peg holes didn't print right for me. I fixed them by inverting a few faces in the STL. On the forward part of the fuel tank, the "intertank" section with the hat stringers didn't print well for me because the stringers are too small for my makerbot resolution. So I smoothed them out in the STL file. That was tedious. For those of you who don't know, this part of the external tank wasn't really a tank. It didn't have liquid inside. Instead it was the transition between the hydrogen tank below and the oxygen tank above. And it carried the thrust from the solid rocket boosters which lofted the tank. So it had to be stiffened with extra stringers. http://science.ksc.nasa.gov/shuttle/technology/sts-newsref/et.html

description.text:
This model was derived from a scan of a small plaster sculpture ("Nach dem Bade" - after the bath) by Swiss artist Hans Hippele (1904 - 1942). It was printed in various sizes and colors during the 2013 series of events "Re:Public Domain". "Re:Public Domain" was initiated by Dock18 Institut für Medienkulturen der Welt, Zurich. The project aims to remind us that, 70 years after an artist's death, all copyright and other intellectual property rights in relation to his art belong to the public who may re-interpret and "remix" it. This work, contributed to the event by FabLab Zürich, exemplifies how this right may be exercised in sculptural art using modern 3D scanning and printing techniques. Other artistic domains such as music, literature or cinematic art were also covered in "Re:Public Domain". http://republicdomain.ch/en/about/
http://zurich.fablab.ch/republic-domain

The 3D point cloud was acquired using a NextEngine scanner. The surface was reconstructed (using a Poisson algorithm), remeshed and cleaned in MeshLab on a Mac. This model has 1602750 vertices, a fairly high resolution.

This is a recreation of DrJekyll's excellent buttons idea, which provides an alternative clipping method and more rigidity in the design. You can find more info on HDMIPI at http://hdmipi.com/
Main photos thanks to Alex Eames http://raspi.tv/

Print in PLA without supports and the buttons face down on your print bed. You will need to get your bed height spot on if you want crisp symbols.  
If you don't wish to use PLA and prefer something like ABS you will need to compensate for shrinkage otherwise it will not clip in tightly, the measurements are quite exact.  
I personally printed with a 0.15mm layer height and tested using both a 0.4mm and a 0.25mm nozzle. It should also work with others.  
To fit it in your HDMIPi slide it through the hole horizontally so the tab behind the external button hooks under the edge, then once its fully slid in push the power button until it's flush. It should click and stay in place. If you have any issues I have supplied the 123D design file (free package) so you can make any required tweaks.
